{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/blog/2018/03/11/installing-jekyll/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Installing Jekyll on Windows","description":"A guide to getting Jekyll up and running on Bash for Windows with Visual Studio Code","date":"2018-03-11T16:00:00.000Z","showReadingTime":null,"toc":null,"presentation":null,"languages":["HTML","SCSS"],"technologies":["Jekyll"]},"excerpt":"Background Jekyll is not officially supported on Windows, but thanks to a new feature of Windows 10, we can still create Jekyll websites on Windows without any…","html":"<h1 id=\"background\" style=\"position:relative;\">Background<a href=\"#background\" aria-label=\"background permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h1>\n<p>Jekyll is not officially supported on Windows, but thanks to a new feature of Windows 10, we can still create Jekyll websites on Windows without any issues. <a href=\"https://jekyllrb.com/docs/windows/#installation\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Jekyll now recommends</a> installing it using <code>Bash on Windows</code>. This guide walks through how to do it and teaches you a little about how Bash and Linux works along the way. This guide assumes you have Windows 10 Fall Creators Update (version 1709) installed. I'll also show you how to set up <a href=\"https://code.visualstudio.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Visual Studio Code</a> to use Bash.</p>\n<h1 id=\"wsl\" style=\"position:relative;\">WSL?<a href=\"#wsl\" aria-label=\"wsl permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h1>\n<p>Jekyll is written in <code>Ruby</code> which itself runs in <code>Bash</code>. Bash is like Linux and Mac's equivalent to CMD or PowerShell. Traditionally installing Ruby in Windows required installing lots of Bash commands that worked as a shim to getting Bash applications running on Windows. Windows 10 has a new feature you can enable that allows you to load a full Linux distribution into a Bash prompt that has access to the Windows file system called <code>WSL (Windows Subsystem for Linux)</code>. This is a better approach to polluting your PowerShell and Command Prompt terminals with Bash commands.</p>\n<h1 id=\"installing-bash\" style=\"position:relative;\">Installing Bash<a href=\"#installing-bash\" aria-label=\"installing bash permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h1>\n<p>Start off by enabling WSL on your machine. Press <i class=\"fab fa-windows\"></i> and search for <em>\"Turn Windows features on or off\"</em>. Tick <em>\"Windows Subsystem for Linux\"</em> and follow the prompts.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 465px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 89.99999999999999%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screenshot of enabling WSL\"\n        title=\"Screenshot of enabling WSL\"\n        src=\"/static/1dbc47f576f1fbbba2e4fa5a1b8f69c4/9ff85/enable-wsl.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/1dbc47f576f1fbbba2e4fa5a1b8f69c4/5a46d/enable-wsl.png 300w,\n/static/1dbc47f576f1fbbba2e4fa5a1b8f69c4/9ff85/enable-wsl.png 465w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 465px) 100vw, 465px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Now enable \"<em>developer mode</em>\" if you haven't done this before. Go to \"<em>Settings</em>\" then \"<em>Update &#x26; Security</em>\" then \"<em>For developers</em>\" on the left-hand side and then finally click on \"<em>Developer mode</em>\".</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 852px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 89.99999999999999%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screenshot of developer settings in Windows 10\"\n        title=\"Screenshot of developer settings in Windows 10\"\n        src=\"/static/7bc0897ca8e37a3a96654f78835fe536/47ff6/enable-developer-mode.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/7bc0897ca8e37a3a96654f78835fe536/5a46d/enable-developer-mode.png 300w,\n/static/7bc0897ca8e37a3a96654f78835fe536/0a47e/enable-developer-mode.png 600w,\n/static/7bc0897ca8e37a3a96654f78835fe536/47ff6/enable-developer-mode.png 852w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 852px) 100vw, 852px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Now open the \"<em>Microsoft Store</em>\" and search for \"<em>Ubuntu</em>\". Click on \"<em>Get</em>\".</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 941px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 64%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screenshot of Ubuntu in the Microsoft Store\"\n        title=\"Screenshot of Ubuntu in the Microsoft Store\"\n        src=\"/static/01eb7802eed5625cce5b0327a1b23965/a8417/install-ubuntu.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/01eb7802eed5625cce5b0327a1b23965/5a46d/install-ubuntu.png 300w,\n/static/01eb7802eed5625cce5b0327a1b23965/0a47e/install-ubuntu.png 600w,\n/static/01eb7802eed5625cce5b0327a1b23965/a8417/install-ubuntu.png 941w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 941px) 100vw, 941px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Once is it installed click on \"<em>Launch</em>\".</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 764px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 31.333333333333336%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screenshot of Ubuntu installed in the Microsoft Store\"\n        title=\"Screenshot of Ubuntu installed in the Microsoft Store\"\n        src=\"/static/394ddbcaafbf59ebf84fbae194a28161/f3c12/installed-ubuntu.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/394ddbcaafbf59ebf84fbae194a28161/5a46d/installed-ubuntu.png 300w,\n/static/394ddbcaafbf59ebf84fbae194a28161/0a47e/installed-ubuntu.png 600w,\n/static/394ddbcaafbf59ebf84fbae194a28161/f3c12/installed-ubuntu.png 764w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 764px) 100vw, 764px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<h1 id=\"setting-up-bash\" style=\"position:relative;\">Setting up Bash<a href=\"#setting-up-bash\" aria-label=\"setting up bash permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h1>\n<p>Wait for Ubuntu to finish installing.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 944px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 55.00000000000001%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screenshot of Ubuntu installed in the Microsoft Store\"\n        title=\"Screenshot of Ubuntu installed in the Microsoft Store\"\n        src=\"/static/4441112db084c2d8772a2fbd558f82fb/966a0/wait-for-ubuntu.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/4441112db084c2d8772a2fbd558f82fb/5a46d/wait-for-ubuntu.png 300w,\n/static/4441112db084c2d8772a2fbd558f82fb/0a47e/wait-for-ubuntu.png 600w,\n/static/4441112db084c2d8772a2fbd558f82fb/966a0/wait-for-ubuntu.png 944w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 944px) 100vw, 944px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>You will then be asked to supply a username and password. This username and password is only used inside the Bash window. To open a Bash window in Windows you need to already be logged in to Windows with a valid Windows account, so don't worry about having a secure password if you're only working on your local dev machine. When typing your password, it appears like you're not typing (e.g. no asterisks appear with each key press in the console). Don't let that fool you, just type your password and press enter. This is the behaviour of Bash whenever you type in a password.</p>\n<p>Inside Ubuntu <code>apt-get</code> is used to install and update applications. Installing applications in Linux is more like installing NPM or NuGet packages, rather than downloading installers like in Windows. Linux has <em>\"repositories\"</em> of packages of software. You must add a repository that contains the software you want to install, then install the package. This means that the vendor of the package can update it inside the repository and the update is then downloaded and installed as part of OS updates.</p>\n<p>Ubuntu keeps a local database/cache of all the packages that are available to install. Firstly, we must update this local database with this command:</p>\n\n        <div class=\"code-copy-wrapper\">\n          <button class=\"code-copy-button\" onClick=\"_codeToClipboard(event);\">Copy</button>\n          <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token function\">sudo</span> <span class=\"token function\">apt-get</span> update -y</code></pre></div>\n        </div>\n<blockquote>\n<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> <code>sudo</code> is the Linux equivalent of \"<em>running as administrator</em>\"\n{: .smaller}</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>You will be asked to enter your Linux password. Again, don't be fooled if nothing appears in the console while you type.</p>\n<p>Now our Ubuntu installation knows about all the latest packages, run the following command to update them all:</p>\n\n        <div class=\"code-copy-wrapper\">\n          <button class=\"code-copy-button\" onClick=\"_codeToClipboard(event);\">Copy</button>\n          <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token function\">sudo</span> <span class=\"token function\">apt-get</span> upgrade -y</code></pre></div>\n        </div>\n<h1 id=\"installing-jekyll-in-bash\" style=\"position:relative;\">Installing Jekyll in Bash<a href=\"#installing-jekyll-in-bash\" aria-label=\"installing jekyll in bash permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h1>\n<p>Now our Ubuntu installation is up to date we can start to follow the instructions from <a href=\"https://jekyllrb.com/docs/windows/#installation-via-bash-on-windows-10\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Jekyll's website</a> to install it. Add a reference to the Jekyll repository by entering the following command:</p>\n\n        <div class=\"code-copy-wrapper\">\n          <button class=\"code-copy-button\" onClick=\"_codeToClipboard(event);\">Copy</button>\n          <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token function\">sudo</span> apt-add-repository ppa:brightbox/ruby-ng</code></pre></div>\n        </div>\n<p>You will be asked to press enter to confirm. Once this has completed update your package database to include the packages in the newly added repository:</p>\n\n        <div class=\"code-copy-wrapper\">\n          <button class=\"code-copy-button\" onClick=\"_codeToClipboard(event);\">Copy</button>\n          <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token function\">sudo</span> <span class=\"token function\">apt-get</span> update -y</code></pre></div>\n        </div>\n<p>Then install Ruby and Jekyll's other dependencies:</p>\n\n        <div class=\"code-copy-wrapper\">\n          <button class=\"code-copy-button\" onClick=\"_codeToClipboard(event);\">Copy</button>\n          <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token function\">sudo</span> <span class=\"token function\">apt-get</span> <span class=\"token function\">install</span> ruby2.3 ruby2.3-dev build-essential dh-autoreconf -y</code></pre></div>\n        </div>\n<p>Ruby has its own form of package system called <code>Gems</code>. A Gem in Ruby is synonymous with an NPM package in Node. Update gems installed by default with Ruby with the following command:</p>\n\n        <div class=\"code-copy-wrapper\">\n          <button class=\"code-copy-button\" onClick=\"_codeToClipboard(event);\">Copy</button>\n          <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">sudo gem update</code></pre></div>\n        </div>\n<p>Then install the <code>jekyll</code> and <code>bundler</code> gems. Bundler is a Ruby thing that Jekyll uses:</p>\n\n        <div class=\"code-copy-wrapper\">\n          <button class=\"code-copy-button\" onClick=\"_codeToClipboard(event);\">Copy</button>\n          <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token function\">sudo</span> gem <span class=\"token function\">install</span> jekyll bundler</code></pre></div>\n        </div>\n<p>You can confirm the installation by entering the following command:</p>\n\n        <div class=\"code-copy-wrapper\">\n          <button class=\"code-copy-button\" onClick=\"_codeToClipboard(event);\">Copy</button>\n          <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">jekyll -v</code></pre></div>\n        </div>\n<h1 id=\"creating-a-jekyll-site\" style=\"position:relative;\">Creating a Jekyll Site<a href=\"#creating-a-jekyll-site\" aria-label=\"creating a jekyll site permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h1>\n<p>This should print something like <code>jekyll 3.7.2</code>. Your C drive is <em>\"mounted\"</em> into the Ubuntu instance running within windows. This means it lives within the <code>/mnt/c/</code> directory inside Bash (note directories as separated by forward slashes rather than back slashes in Linux). So, to change directory to <code>C:\\_Code\\Git\\</code> you would type the following:</p>\n\n        <div class=\"code-copy-wrapper\">\n          <button class=\"code-copy-button\" onClick=\"_codeToClipboard(event);\">Copy</button>\n          <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\"><span class=\"token builtin class-name\">cd</span> /mnt/c/_Code/Git/</code></pre></div>\n        </div>\n<p>CD to the directory you wish to put your Jekyll website's folder into. Run the following command to create a new Jekyll website (which in turn, creates a folder for your website). Obviously replace yourwebsitenamehere with what you want to call your site:</p>\n\n        <div class=\"code-copy-wrapper\">\n          <button class=\"code-copy-button\" onClick=\"_codeToClipboard(event);\">Copy</button>\n          <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">jekyll new yourwebsitenamehere</code></pre></div>\n        </div>\n<h1 id=\"setting-up-visual-studio-code\" style=\"position:relative;\">Setting up Visual Studio Code<a href=\"#setting-up-visual-studio-code\" aria-label=\"setting up visual studio code permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h1>\n<p>If you haven't installed Visual Studio Code, do so now. Open VS Code inside the folder the <code>jekyll new</code> command created. You can do this by using the file menu or by right clicking in the folder in file explorer. Once you have opened VS Code in the folder click on \"<em>File</em>\" then \"<em>Preferences</em>\" then <em>\"Settings\"</em>.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 903px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 82%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screenshot of Visual Studio Code with the file menu open\"\n        title=\"Screenshot of Visual Studio Code with the file menu open\"\n        src=\"/static/ed6e76e7326f46d248c484270f3ed168/c4b7c/vs-code-open-settings.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/ed6e76e7326f46d248c484270f3ed168/5a46d/vs-code-open-settings.png 300w,\n/static/ed6e76e7326f46d248c484270f3ed168/0a47e/vs-code-open-settings.png 600w,\n/static/ed6e76e7326f46d248c484270f3ed168/c4b7c/vs-code-open-settings.png 903w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 903px) 100vw, 903px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Then click on Workspace settings on the right-hand side.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 968px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 37.99999999999999%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screenshot of Visual Studio Code with the settings window open\"\n        title=\"Screenshot of Visual Studio Code with the settings window open\"\n        src=\"/static/53bd21899de64015cc7eec47130ca1ce/e2310/vs-code-settings.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/53bd21899de64015cc7eec47130ca1ce/5a46d/vs-code-settings.png 300w,\n/static/53bd21899de64015cc7eec47130ca1ce/0a47e/vs-code-settings.png 600w,\n/static/53bd21899de64015cc7eec47130ca1ce/e2310/vs-code-settings.png 968w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 968px) 100vw, 968px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Place the following JSON in Workspace settings:</p>\n\n        <div class=\"code-copy-wrapper\">\n          <button class=\"code-copy-button\" onClick=\"_codeToClipboard(event);\">Copy</button>\n          <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"json\"><pre class=\"language-json\"><code class=\"language-json\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n  <span class=\"token property\">\"terminal.integrated.shell.windows\"</span><span class=\"token operator\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"C:\\\\Windows\\\\System32\\\\bash.exe\"</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n        </div>\n<p>This will ensure Bash is used in the VS Code's integrated terminal when you open this folder.</p>\n<p>Now open the integrated terminal by pressing <code>CTRL</code> + <code>'</code> (that's a single quote). You may be asked to confirm your choice of using Bash in the terminal, click \"<em>Allow</em>\".</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1144px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 7.666666666666668%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABQAAAACCAYAAABYBvyLAAAACXBIWXMAACToAAAk6AGCYwUcAAAATklEQVQI123IQQrAIAxEUY9QYki8eKQpJB51RFcWXDyG+SUzEBEYYyAzf1a/fXeHmaH3fjDY+6GoKkQErbVt/dOtMTOICLXWjdYS4WHBBKJjUVAZQnuCAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screenshot of Visual Studio Code asking to use bash\"\n        title=\"Screenshot of Visual Studio Code asking to use bash\"\n        src=\"/static/a904a903fcbf9bfae50e200256883c98/ee3fb/vs-code-bash-confirmation.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/a904a903fcbf9bfae50e200256883c98/5a46d/vs-code-bash-confirmation.png 300w,\n/static/a904a903fcbf9bfae50e200256883c98/0a47e/vs-code-bash-confirmation.png 600w,\n/static/a904a903fcbf9bfae50e200256883c98/ee3fb/vs-code-bash-confirmation.png 1144w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1144px) 100vw, 1144px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>You will now see a Bash terminal in VS Code:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1200px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 22.666666666666664%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABQAAAAFCAYAAABFA8wzAAAACXBIWXMAACToAAAk6AGCYwUcAAAAh0lEQVQY042OUQ7DIAxDuQcktJARsjJp97+cp1DtZ0NVP6w4dvSUYNqhqniaQVuD9Y6uilJ2iFQwM4hozl+llGBmGGOg1goRQWjvA20caPbC/jDk0pCrYpOOIroE+v7NHBpjnLv7kDIjeUEM4g2cT7knzpcfrvLAHs7inLTQFfQfeOPoLsyBH42siHRkdyLVAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Screenshot of Visual Studio Code&#39;s integrated shell using Bash\"\n        title=\"Screenshot of Visual Studio Code&#39;s integrated shell using Bash\"\n        src=\"/static/459df02153282181e44f3ac4ef0a96b0/c1b63/vs-code-bash-terminal.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/459df02153282181e44f3ac4ef0a96b0/5a46d/vs-code-bash-terminal.png 300w,\n/static/459df02153282181e44f3ac4ef0a96b0/0a47e/vs-code-bash-terminal.png 600w,\n/static/459df02153282181e44f3ac4ef0a96b0/c1b63/vs-code-bash-terminal.png 1200w,\n/static/459df02153282181e44f3ac4ef0a96b0/844cc/vs-code-bash-terminal.png 1306w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>You can now run Jekyll commands in the integrated terminal. To launch your Jekyll website run the following command:</p>\n\n        <div class=\"code-copy-wrapper\">\n          <button class=\"code-copy-button\" onClick=\"_codeToClipboard(event);\">Copy</button>\n          <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"bash\"><pre class=\"language-bash\"><code class=\"language-bash\">jekyll serve</code></pre></div>\n        </div>","tableOfContents":"<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#background\">Background</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#wsl\">WSL?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#installing-bash\">Installing Bash</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#setting-up-bash\">Setting up Bash</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#installing-jekyll-in-bash\">Installing Jekyll in Bash</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#creating-a-jekyll-site\">Creating a Jekyll Site</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#setting-up-visual-studio-code\">Setting up Visual Studio Code</a></li>\n</ul>","timeToRead":5},"prev":{"fields":{"slug":"/blog/2018/04/10/git-presentation/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Git Presentation"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/blog/2017/09/30/introducing-akka-testing-helpers-di/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"UPDATE: Introducing Akka Testing Helpers"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/blog/2018/03/11/installing-jekyll/","prevSlug":"/blog/2018/04/10/git-presentation/","nextSlug":"/blog/2017/09/30/introducing-akka-testing-helpers-di/"}},"staticQueryHashes":["3525937013"]}